<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="81" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="81">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="81">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Plangiopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plangiopsis adeps" order="Orthoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adeps">Plangiopsis adeps</taxonomicName>
is the largest species of the genus; only females from Cameroon (Lolodorf) were described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Karsch, F" journalOrPublisher="Stettiner entomologische Zeitung" pageId="14" pageNumber="91" pagination="242 - 359" title="Neue Orthopteren aus dem tropischen Afrika." url="http://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/36013page/250/mode/1up" volume="57" year="1896">Karsch (1896)</bibRefCitation>
. New distribution data now suggest that this species is widespread throughout Cameroon and Central African Republic to the Ivory Coast and Togo. Sexual characters of the male, previously undescribed, are the following: cerci slender and long, in-curved and a little up-curved, sub-genital plate narrow and long, ending with a v-shaped concavity, styli long. The stridulatory file is comparatively long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
